<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-790-555  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 790 555.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Dec 31 1990 v7 n53 p21(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Network gives police ready access to an array of data; Nevadapolice get new weapon in war on crime.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Molloy, Maureen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Nevada law enforcement agencies implement a centralstore-and-forward message switching system called the LawEnforcement Message Switching (LEMS) system.andP;  The system uses twoUnisys 2200/401 mainframes to handle up to 200,000 transactionseach day.andP;  The system accesses data bases from state lawenforcement agencies, university police agencies, federal andCalifornia agencies.andP;  Officers on patrol receive responses toinquiries within seconds.andP;  The system links the mainframes to aUnisys Distributed Communications Processor supporting 32dedicated lines to various police departments around Nevada.andP;  Themainframes act as gateways to the Federal Bureau ofInvestigations' National Crime Information Center and National LawEnforcement Telecommunications System.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Law EnforcementNetworksData BasesInformation ProcessingNevadaMainframe Computers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>